  "title": "Finding the Why",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0be8f74104595a2a",
      "text": "We learn, deeply learn, when there is a personal purpose and personal meaning."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d4e22c7e4e955346",
      "text": "But we hope, deep in our hearts, that our learning can be shared, that it might become meaningful for others, that it matters. We learn in the hope that we have made meaning not only for ourselves but for others in the short time we have on this beautiful planet."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2f88c5ed433f73ba",
      "text": "That, perhaps in a small way, we have made a difference, that we made a tiny dent in the universe."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e97ba25c4d4fad6b",
      "text": "That is my Why. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "533fd9129156550c",
      "text": "There was this moment when I realized that the heavy work of raising a family and building a business career was, for the most part, over – my kids were launched into their own lives and I had learned much from running different companies. I began to ask myself if I was to make a larger dent, what [[Audacious Aspiration]] could I courageously walk into that would challenge my very being?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b6fbc01346d20dfb",
      "text": "Yes, a [[Quixotic Quest]] where the windmill becomes a dragon – a quest that might inspire others to also live into an audacity. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8d8cebbaa0a354e0",
      "text": "It wasn't long before I came to realize that the windmill at which I would tilt my lance was our education systems, wondering if we could ever reimagine how we educate the next generation, recognizing that our current systems were so deeply broken, crippling our youth, crippling our future."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a3b800b660157ee6",
      "text": "What might happen, I wondered, if we were able to unleash the creative genius of each child so that they were all empowered to change the world? "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b5d4ffdec29d1cb0",
      "text": "Now, that would be amazing. Crazy thinking, yes, but amazing. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "8dd035e4473b0b49",
      "text": "There is broad agreement that radical transformation of how we educate is needed – Sir Ken Robinson's TED talk _Do Schools Kill Creativity_ is one of the most viewed talks ever given. The question that gnawed at me was how could such radical transformation happen in such complex and entrenched systems."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ebce226955abe32a",
      "text": "I wondered, might the explosive creative potential that I experienced guiding a software company that had embraced an [[Agile Mindset]] help guide a process of radical transformation in education?"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "605062139d2c8811",
      "text": "I am not a professional educator – I am an outsider, a foreigner in this land of education. But as a business consultant and as a corporate leader, I have always been a learner – a leader that sought to inspire learning in others so that, together, we could create the amazing."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "1d593fecd7766ca8",
      "text": "My quixotic journey in education began at Franklin High School in Portland, Oregon, and led me to Dayton Middle and High School in Dayton, Oregon, where I partnered with Jami Fluke, their principal. In just a few years, a radical transformation happened, amazing many – a story that was told in a book called _[https://dayton.fed.wiki/welcome-visitors.html The Dayton Experiment]_."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "361d53f9cc4f6a99",
      "text": "I remember the moment that this book was ready to be written. It happened when I walked into Jenni Shilhanek's 7th-grade class, a class she called Genius Hour 2.0, and watched how she had taken practices of Agile from my software industry and transformed them into a new learning practice in her classroom that was unleashing genius everywhere – it was, simply, electrifying."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "6735cc8b625d4e18",
      "text": "So I set about to write the book with the help of Jami and Ward Cunningham, one of the founders of the Agile movement – a story that ended with a description of Jenni's classroom where I shared what we called [[The Dayton Practice]]. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "70629a6e0c0d7f79",
      "text": "But it wasn't until covid turned our world upside down that we realized the need to quickly transform this practice into a learning framework. A framework that we could share with educators around the world that might open new doors for radical change. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "44d46f3c3c20f74d",
      "text": "During the chaotic first two weeks of school closure due to the pandemic, a small group of school leaders not only personally experienced this new framework, but defined it and wrote its guidebook."
    },
    {
